<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="162" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1189,2008]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1260,1287]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: This species was originally described as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1859" box="[990,1144,1261,1288]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrolepis">
<emphasis box="[990,1144,1261,1288]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">S. macrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="King, F. W." box="[1192,1332,1261,1288]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="1 - 52" refId="ref20436" refString="King, F. W. (1962) Systematics of Lesser Antillean lizards of the genus Sphaerodactylus. Bulletin of the Florida State Museum, Biological Sciences, 7, 1 - 52." type="journal article" year="1962">King (1962)</bibRefCitation>
and was elevated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Powell, R. &amp; Henderson, R. W." box="[290,611,1297,1323]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="288 - 290" refId="ref22195" refString="Powell, R. &amp; Henderson, R. W. (2001) On the taxonomic status of some Lesser Antillean Lizards. Caribbean Journal of Science, 37, 288 - 290." type="journal article" year="2001">Powell &amp; Henderson (2001)</bibRefCitation>
who differentiated this species on the basis of 1) dorsal scales with hair bearing scale organs, with only one hair each along the dorso-distal edge; 2) maximum SVL size of 
<quantity box="[1271,1350,1333,1360]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" unit="mm" value="24.0">24 mm</quantity>
(
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" unit="mm" value="21.0" valueMax="24.0" valueMin="18.0">18–24 mm</quantity>
, x̅ = 21.7); 3) having a higher mean number of midbody scale rows (48.4 ± 1.5); and 4) weak sexual dichroma- tism nor ontogenetic variation (
<bibRefCitation author="King, F. W." box="[504,628,1405,1431]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="1 - 52" refId="ref20436" refString="King, F. W. (1962) Systematics of Lesser Antillean lizards of the genus Sphaerodactylus. Bulletin of the Florida State Museum, Biological Sciences, 7, 1 - 52." type="journal article" year="1962">King 1962</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, R. &amp; Schwartz, A." box="[640,938,1405,1432]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="193 - 260" refId="ref23344" refString="Thomas, R. &amp; Schwartz, A. (1966) Sphaerodactylus (Gekkonidae) in the greater Puerto Rico region. Bulletin of the Florida State Museum, Biological Sciences, 10, 193 - 260." type="journal article" year="1966">Thomas &amp; Schwartz 1966</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Nava, S. S. &amp; Lindsay, C. R. &amp; Powell, R. &amp; Henderson, R. W." box="[957,1162,1405,1432]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="1 - 2" refId="ref21325" refString="Nava, S. S., Lindsay, C. R., Powell, R. &amp; Henderson, R. W. (2002) Sphaerodactylus parvus. Catalog of American Amphibians and Reptiles, 752, 1 - 2." type="journal article" year="2002">
Nava 
<emphasis box="[1024,1081,1405,1431]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">et al.</emphasis>
(2002)
</bibRefCitation>
described six additional differences with other members of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1859" box="[580,730,1441,1468]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrolepis">
<emphasis box="[580,730,1441,1468]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">S. macrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex: 5) less bulky habitus; 6) ventral scales keeled on the sides of abdomen of some specimens (
<bibRefCitation author="King, F. W." box="[649,772,1477,1504]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="1 - 52" refId="ref20436" refString="King, F. W. (1962) Systematics of Lesser Antillean lizards of the genus Sphaerodactylus. Bulletin of the Florida State Museum, Biological Sciences, 7, 1 - 52." type="journal article" year="1962">King 1962</bibRefCitation>
); 7) less densely pigmented throat; 8) less conspicuous head patterns; 9) smaller scapular patch on females; and 10) ten toe lamellae on the fourth toe (9–11; 
<bibRefCitation author="King, F. W." box="[1248,1372,1513,1540]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="1 - 52" refId="ref20436" refString="King, F. W. (1962) Systematics of Lesser Antillean lizards of the genus Sphaerodactylus. Bulletin of the Florida State Museum, Biological Sciences, 7, 1 - 52." type="journal article" year="1962">King 1962</bibRefCitation>
). Our work shows that only characters 2, 3, 4, and 9 are actually diagnostic (Appendix 2). SVL Min/Max is 12.17/ 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.639" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" unit="mm" value="26.39">26.39 mm</quantity>
. Additional diagnostic traits for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="King" authorityYear="1962" box="[566,671,1586,1612]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parvus">
<emphasis box="[566,671,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">S. parvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
include a scapular patch that can be brown and black (also present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1859" box="[182,335,1621,1648]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrolepis">
<emphasis box="[182,335,1621,1648]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">S. macrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); males and females with no well-defined occipital spots and postorbital line; pale or yellowish ocelli from the scapular patch very close or united; males and females with no well-defined head patterns; males and females without dorsal lines, color pattern more ‘salt and pepper’. Females seem to have a more defined gular pattern than males.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1189,2008]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,348,1764,1791]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">Color in life</emphasis>
: Color of male and female varies from pale pink to brown, with scattered dark brown scales (
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, R. &amp; Schwartz, A." box="[159,456,1801,1828]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="193 - 260" refId="ref23344" refString="Thomas, R. &amp; Schwartz, A. (1966) Sphaerodactylus (Gekkonidae) in the greater Puerto Rico region. Bulletin of the Florida State Museum, Biological Sciences, 10, 193 - 260." type="journal article" year="1966">Thomas &amp; Schwartz 1966</bibRefCitation>
) producing a salt and pepper effect on dorsum. Head and tail color usually lighter than the body, scapular patch bicolored (brown anteriorly and black posteriorly) with light margin surrounding the patch. Males and females with a marked pattern on throat.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="162" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1189,2008]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1908,1935]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">Distribution</emphasis>
: The only member, aside from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1859" box="[697,848,1909,1936]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrolepis">
<emphasis box="[697,848,1909,1936]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">S. macrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1859" box="[934,1085,1909,1936]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphaerodactylidae" genus="Sphaerodactylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrolepis">
<emphasis box="[934,1085,1909,1936]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">S. macrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex found outside of the Puerto Rican Bank. This species is found exclusively on the 
<collectingCountry box="[885,983,1945,1971]" name="Anguilla" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">Anguilla</collectingCountry>
Bank near the northern end of the Lesser Antilles, including the islands of 
<collectingCountry box="[521,622,1981,2007]" name="Anguilla" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">Anguilla</collectingCountry>
, St.-Barthélémy, St.-Martin, Tintamarre I., and Dog. I.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
